04943nam a22007815i 9780271085531DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20192020pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710855317 a10.1515/97802710855312doi  a(DE-B1597)584385  a(OCoLC)1253313038  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aML1427.2b.H36 2019eb 7aHIS0130002bisacsh04a780.944/361090322231 aHammond, Nicholas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Powers of Sound and Song in Early Modern Paris /cNicholas Hammond. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2019] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b10 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerspectives on Sensory History ;v100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tAuthor’s Note -- tIntroduction -- tPart I The Power of Sound -- t1. The Sounds of Paris -- t2. Singers and Listeners -- t3. Informé de tout -- tPart II Chausson’s Song -- t4. The Death and Afterlife of Jacques Chausson -- t5. Guitaut, Condé, and the Cordon bleu -- t6. Different Worlds -- tConclusion -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe long and spectacular reign of Louis XIV of France is typically described in overwhelmingly visual terms. In this book, Nicholas Hammond takes a sonic approach to this remarkable age, opening our ears to the myriad ways in which sound revealed the complex acoustic dimensions of class, politics, and sexuality in seventeenth-century Paris.The discovery in the French archives of a four-line song from 1661 launched Hammond’s research into the lives of the two men referenced therein—Jacques Chausson and Guillaume de Guitaut. In retracing the lives of these two men (one sentenced to death by burning and the other appointed to the Ordre du Saint-Esprit), Hammond makes astonishing discoveries about each man and the ways in which their lives intersected, all in the context of the sounds and songs heard in the court of Louis XIV and on the streets and bridges of Paris. Hammond’s study shows how members of the elite and lower classes in Paris crossed paths in unexpected ways and, moreover, how noise in the ancien régime was central to questions of crime and punishment: street singing was considered a crime in itself, and yet street singers flourished, circulating information about crimes that others may have committed, while political and religious authorities wielded the powerful sounds of sermons and public executions to provide moral commentaries, to control crime, and to inflict punishment.This innovative study explores the theoretical, social, cultural, and historical contexts of the early modern Parisian soundscape. It will appeal to scholars interested in sound studies and the history of sexuality as well as those who study the culture, literature, and history of early modern France.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aCity soundszFrancezParisxHistoryy17th century. 0aSongs, FrenchzFrancezParisy17th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh  aLouis XIV.  aParis.  aPont-Neuf.  aSong.  aearly modern.  aseventeenth century.  asexuality.  asound studies.  astreet songs.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311074521440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271085531?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271085531423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271085531/original  a978-3-11-074521-4  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  a